reviewText:
"The Conjuring 2" is great. This is how the story goes: Lorraine and Ed Warren travel to north London to help a single mother raising four children alone in a house plagued by malicious spirits.

The cast led by Patrick Wilson (as Ed) & Vera Farmiga (as Lorraine) is great. The directing by James Wan (who also produced and co-wrote the story & screenplay) is great. The story by Wan, Chad & Carey Hayes and the screenplay by Wan, Chad & Carey Hayes and David Leslie Johnson is great.

The music by Joseph Bishara (who makes an appearance as a Demon) is great. The cinematography by Don Burgess is great. The film editing by Kirk Morri is great. The casting by Anne McCarthy, Kellie Roy & Rose Wicksteed is great. The production design by Julie Berghoff is great. The art direction by A. Todd Holland & Andrew Rothschild is great. The set decoration by Liz Griffiths & Sophie Neudorfer, set dressings by Daniel Ainslie, Don Cinderella, Katie Gauvin & Andre Rivera is great. The costume design by Kristin M. Burke is great. The make-up effects by Eleanor Sabaduquia is great. The special effects supervised by Matt Kutcher & Chris Reynolds is great. The visual effects supervised by Colin Strause & Ariel Velasco-Shaw is great. The stunts coordinated by Joel Kramer & John Rottger is great.

This is a great horror movie sequel that is entertaining, scary and well-done. This is just as great as the first "Conjuring". Patrick Wilson & Vera Farmiga are solid again as usual as Ed & Lorraine. James Wan has directed another great movie (horror or otherwise). This is one of the best movies of the summer, so far and also one of the better sequels (in general) of the year, as well, too.

The Conjuring 2 delivers on a number of levels. Its terrifying  inflicting the audience with numerous horrific scenes. While the horror is ramped up it never resorts to being cheesy or gratuitous. The original unfolds more like the traditional tale of the supernatural haunted house, while the sequel is poignant in the way it zeros in closely into the family. The characters at the heart of the horror become much more than merely the victims who the Warrens seek to save from evil entities. The family and their neighbours prove themselves to be strong characters and are portrayed to be every bit as interesting as the Warrens.

The sometimes slow pace of the movie heightens the impending dread and emotional intensity of the familys plight. The Conjuring 2 is more complex than the original with more twists and turns. Despite a larger cast of interested onlookers coupled with greater publicity of this haunting, ultimately the family are left more helpless when an unrelenting sceptic finally undermines their credibility. The sequel is a compassionate story that doesnt simply play to scare. Even though the victims are terrified and helpless against a devious and powerful entity, they are brave and resilient.
The setting is very prosaic and urban reflecting 1970s London, and it blends supernatural and family drama seamlessly. The main plot focuses on the haunted house, the subplot is more personal and zeros in on Lorraines vulnerability and courage brought on by her powerful psychic ability. Ultimately, the two narrative strands stories converge dramatically to bring the film to its climax.

The Good:
Get used to it, but I'm going to be telling you often that director James Wan (Saw, Insidious, The Conjuring) is an absolute MASTER of horror. Just like in The Conjuring, he teases you with the stereotypical horror tactics that we've all seen in other horror films. Then he throws you a bunch of curve balls so you'll never really know what to expect. To make things even scarier, he even has the characters in the movie do what you or I would probably do in their situations. For example, if you saw a ghost, you'd probably run, right? I know I would.

If you allow me to nerd out a bit, I have to bring your attention to some of the unique camera angles that are used in the film. With the many horror films I've seen, I've never seen the ones he used in one of the "interview sessions", for example. (You'll know which one I'm referring to when you see it)

I would like to think that I'm one of those who don't scare easy, but this movie had me cowering in my seat the entire time. It was simply so intense and suspenseful that I had to check my heart rate a few times. (I'm pretty sure I died twice)

If you're a fan of James Wan's other work, then you may also catch on to the fact that there are a lot of similar themes that the movies share. The rules in his "horror universe" are almost the same.
I think overall, the characters all delivered. Patrick Wilson and Vera Farmiga continue to share great on screen chemistry.  As for the ghost in the film....it was scary. Matter of fact, I'm still in the process of trying to forget it, so that's all I'll say about it. :-/

The Bad:
This is 100% me simply nitpicking, but I was a little disappointed by the final moments of the movie. I've seen a ton of exorcism movies, and I thought that the final wrap up was a tad bit rushed.

The Reason:
If you liked Insidious 1 or 2, or the Conjuring (review), then youll enjoy this. I think its fair to say that this will probably be the best horror film for the year. Did I already mention that James Wan is the MASTER of horror? Honestly, I just don't think there's much of a comparison for another director in this decade.

Just like in one of my previous horror reviews, I do want to clarify the difference between "scary" and "Creepy". "Scary" means that it will have moments that shock you with jump scares. "Creepy" is all about the overall feeling and atmosphere that sticks with you well after the movie is over. Many horror films today simply don't find a nice balance between the two, or they just pile on a bunch of blood and gore to overwhelm you.
James Wan, in my opinion, transcended even himself by blending creepy and scary even more than before. I think that the Conjuring 2 is more than worth the watch and is a "Must See"in my book. Ill tell you this, Im not going to London, I don't like nuns anymore, and I will never buy my children a fire truck.

Rating:  9.5/10

A solid, if not great, horror film and a worthy follow-up to the future classic first film. Once again, we follow the Warrens as they investigate a haunting, this time involving a lower-middle-class British family. This is based on a true story, the famous Enfield Haunting--which inspired a pretty creepy documentary you might want to check out. It's a terrific setting for a haunted house/possession story. Set in the sixties, this film is actually a prequel to the first Conjuring, exploring what events brought Elizabeth Warren back into the spiritualism business, as well as what kept her out in the first place.

The youngest girl, played by Madison Wolfe, is especially great in the role of one of the daughters who draws the focus of a nasty demon. There are a great MANY jump-scares in this movie, more than any of Wan's other films. But James Wan has become a new master of horror and he knows how to play an audience like a fiddle. I admire his craft and love that he has almost single-handedly inspired a whole new renaissance of the horror genre. No dumb teenagers or high body count here, just pure adrenaline-inducing tension.

Like the Conjuring did for Anabelle, this film sets up a spin-off with a frightful nun, who looks like a combination of Marilyn Manson and...well...Marilyn Manson. Anyway, if you're in the mood for a tight little scare-fest, and you've got a strong enough heart to withstand a barrage of jump-scares, check out The Conjuring 2.

Quick Story:  Another Ed and Lorraine Warren tale this time set in England.  A family is tortured by a demonic spirit as the Warrens try to help.

Acting was mostly good. There were just a few moments I felt the words coming out of Ed Warren's mouth weren't carrying enough emotion such as the moment he continues on in the house when Lorraine is on the outside, it felt very flat there.  A few times Lorraine was overacting and trying to be too dramatic at times too.

Overall, Throughout the over two hours, this movie hovers between average to dumb to decent creepy.  It's a fairly long movie especially for a horror film.  Since it is so long, it takes a fairly long time to develop.  I liked the nun demon, that was pretty freaky looking and powerful.  The old man ghost kept hovering between being really dumb and cheesy to freaky too. I thought the jump scares used by this ghost in the 1st half couldn't have been any cheesier..they might as well had him yell "boo" each time..It had that feel.  There were some camera and editing effects I enjoyed - the moment the little girl blurred to the old man and back while in the arm chair. Otherwise the other effects were the same door slams, things moving on their own, things you'd expect from a possession or demon movie. Still this movie while okay didn't live up to matching it's predecessor.

 The thing I hated about the movie was how this film tried to connect the Amityville house with the England house by using the nun ghost.  The film begins at Amityville which had zero connection to the England case.  The England case also had not yet started as it began much later with the girls using the Ouija board which conjured the old man ghost.  Tons of dumb jump scares in the 1st hour as I mentioned earlier  (like when he yells "My house!"  at the television scene, or the tent jump scares scream "Ahh!' in the not once but TWICE in one movie - ...the first time the boy 1st half of the film.. and again Ed Warren near the end of the film, sorry script writing team, you suck).  So somehow the nun ghost transports to England from Amityville and the old man ghost is of no consequence in the end.  He actually becomes even less scary and more of a sympathetic character by the end as he helps Lorraine.  He just disappears too.  It's never even discussed why that nun demon was at both locations and also present at the Warren home.  So I don't hate the movie but I think like most sequels doesn't quite hit the same mark.  It's produced well, decent enough acting to enjoy this movie, but it's average at best.

There are not too many horror movies, or movies in general, anymore I feel I can take, because I feel a lot has fallen out of hand. This one is different. The director, James Wan, said that he wants to bring respect back to horror films, and that is exactly what I saw. While the movie does still follow its genre of being scary, it also has a very nice sense of sweetness to it. The family is very grateful, there is a love story between the Warrens, and there are special moments in this movie which are actually heart warming. I love kids, and I hate to see them be put up to wrong roles in other movies. In this movie, I love the cast, it was very scary, and it fulfills the horror theme. This is the type of horror I recommend, the kind that does not focus on gore, provocativeness, and crude humor. This felt like an old fashion horror, and I always look forward to James Wan's works since he has a very different approach.

Easily one of the scariest movies I have watched in a long history of movie watching. I am 45, and can quite frankly say this is one of the more visceral and frightening movies made in recent memory - all without one bit of needless slash and gore. Only two camps of people will come not to enjoy this film - those craving only spurting blood and the occasional half-naked woman, and those vehemently opposed to the idea that the Bible may actually be telling us the truth about Lucifer and his allies.

"Well, there's, uh, nothing we can do about that," says one of the police constables as they beat a hasty retreat after seeing something spooky in the Hodgson household.

I started watching The Conjuring 2 in the wee hours - 2am? 3am? - and got scurred enough that I quit watching until much later when it was light out. James Wan is a beast, man. Guy knows how to make legit spine-tinglers, knows how to stage a scene in such a way that you're anxiously peering around corners even before the camera gets there. The Conjuring 2 is a scary movie. You will get scurred.

We catch up with the paranormal world's preeminent power couple, Ed and Lorraine Warren, fresh off their investigation of the Amityville haunting, up in New York. The Warrens are riding high on publicity, conducting interviews, going on talk shows, never mind that, everywhere they go, there seem to be these expert academics who throw shade at them.

A year later, in 1977, deep in the holiday season, the church reaches out to the Warrens and asks them to get to Enfield, North London to help a harried single mother of four, one of whom is her possessed daughter. The Enfield haunting will be one of their most terrifying cases.

The Conjuring 2 meets all the conventions of horror cinema. So it's got that in common with lesser horror films. What elevates The Conjuring 2 is the consummate way Wan works his craft. But toss in, too, the expert writing. The acting performances are top notch. Patrick Wilson and Vera Farmiga as the ghostbusting Warrens are excellent yet again, lending genuine human drama and delivering an astonishingly grounded relationship as a couple. Their marriage feels like the real thing. One new ingredient is Madison Wolfe who is fantastic as the tormented 11-year-old Janet Hodgson. I appreciate the tight-knitness of not only the Warrens but also of the Hodgson family. You just feel so frightened for them all.

Me, I was biting my nails throughout wondering how they can possibly check the malevolent entity. The parapsychologist on site scornfully maintains that Peggy Hodgson, the mother, is either perpetrating a hoax or having a case of hysterical neuroses. Distressingly, Lorraine Warren's second sight is being clouded. The one thing she did glimpse in a vision is that her husband is doomed to a horrifying death. Also, there's a demonic nun waiting to pounce from the shadows.

I love the cinematography and the sound design, both working in concert to deliver genuine scare jumps. No fake-outs here. No "oh, it's just the cat" or "oh, it's just your jerk friend pranking you." In this one, when you hear something creeping, buster, it means THERE IS SOMETHING CREEPING! Great fun.

Having been reasonably entertained by the original, I recently viewed director James Wan's THE CONJURING 2.  Patrick Wilson and Vera Farmiga (wolf howl) reprise their roles as paranormal "investigators" Ed and Lorraine Warren; this time, they're heading across the pond to north London to investigate the demonic disturbances of the Hodgson household.  Poor Lorraine has a psychic connection to the demon making all the fuss, and when--gasp!--she recalls its name she has more power over it than Superman.

Reasonably entertained.  That's so appropriate an expression for this sequel.  The effects work--director Wan has a thing for upside down crosses.  And the visual "Gotchas!" are plentiful.  Actress Bonnie Aarons is sensationally creepy as the demonic nun in dire need of a dentist; hers is the face you never want to wake up to after a Saturday night bender.  Yes, this sequel is formulaic, predictable, and hopelessly contrived, but for 90
minutes of horror genre indulgence THE CONURING 2 manages to entertain, and give you a couple of goose bumps along the way.  Bring your toothbrush.
~D. Mikels, Esq.

I am a big fan of Ed and Lorraine Warren and am very familiar with most of their cases. This movie is excellent and based on true events. Excellent if you are into demonic related material. It is scary but does not contain bloody or any kind of violent material. Note: The only real connection between the movie 'The Conjuring' and this movie .....is Ed and Lorraine, and the general kinds of cases they usually become involved with. Two entirely separate cases, countries. The Warrens took the first case by their own choice via desperate plea from a family member. In this movie, the Catholic Church requested they access the situation on their behalf. Actors playing Ed and Lorraine are spot on! I love this movie and have watched it many times. Ed and Lorraine Warren should be made Saints. May Ed rest in peace he was a great gift to the world. Lorraine is as well and I still see her occasionally assisting with a case. Hint: She is sitting in the front row in the college lecture hall! She is still so cute ...all dressed up. (cameo). Glad to see you incognito Lorraine! Thank you for all the good you do in the world. :-)

A blockbuster, terror epic of a ghost story but lacking the near perfect, raw potency of the original film. This is largely due to the design choices for its main antagonist, Valak the demon that terrorizes the Hodgson family. One of its manifestations, The Crooked Man is very much a modern creature/character design. The sequence in itself is visually stunning, played beautifully by an actual character actor, but grievously misplaced in the films 70s setting. It also doesnt help that Valaks demonic nun impression bears a striking resemblance to Marilyn Manson. That being said, theres still plenty of original scares thanks to James Wans slow but sure ascent to modern Master of Horror status. Now, if only he would stop being distracted by fast cars and aquatic superheroes.

The Enfield Poltergeist: Living the Horror (13min) - A great featurette of the orginal family that was haunted by the Enfield Poltergeist.
Creating Crooked (7min) - A fascinating focus piece on Javier Botet and the creation process of the Crooked man.
The Conjuring 2: Hollywood's Haunted Stage (5min) - A paranormal investigator talks about the set of the conjuring 2 and claims that it is in fact haunted.
The Sounds of Scare (7min) - on scoring the film

The Conjuring 2

Most of the reviews of this film are positive, as can easily be seen.  This is the second film with the same two actors portraying real-life Ed and Lorraine Warren, two self-appointed exorcists who are/were devout Catholics.  I say "self-appointed" because they aren't clergy (whom the Catholic church would traditionally use for an exorcism if they believed one was warranted--sorry about the unintended pun there) nor, as far as I know, did the Catholic church officially acknowledge them as such although they gained something of a reputation, certainly in the United States, for their activities.

The first film was about the Amityville Horror and the Lutz family who inhabited a house in which formerly a mass murder took place.  The Lutz family came to believe their son was possessed by the same evil spirit that supposedly caused a man previously to murder his whole family there.  The Warrens intervened and gained nationwide publicity as a result of the case.  Basically I enjoyed watching the movie including some specials on the disc in which several actual family members (but not the "possessed" son) were interviewed.  There remains controversy (of course) over the whole Amityville case.

In "Conjuring Two", as a result of their reputation, they get called in to investigate a case going on in England.  This is a family of a now-single mom struggling to raise three kids: two daughters and a son.  The father allegedly left her and got involved with "a woman around the corner" with whom he now has a pair of twin kids.  In Conjuring 2, things begin to go bad for this family when the younger girl is persuaded by a school friend to mess around with a sort of Ouija board.  From there, things rapidly grow worse.

I won't reveal much more about the plot details, but in the film the Warrens come in and, of course, "save the day".  They believe this is much worse than your run-of-the-mill evil ghost or possession; that in fact a Demon is taking possession of one of the children.  You can't get much higher up than that in the hierarchy of evil I guess, except Satan himself.

A lot of remarkable phenomena occur in the film.  This would be physical phenomena, that would be at least potentially much more easily verifiable than telepathy, precognition or other more subjective and internal events.  If things had really happened as portrayed, it should have caused a really major stir.

Checking other sources you'll see that in England this was not labeled a case of demonic possession nor haunting nor a ghost.  It was termed the "Enfield Poltergeist".  Reading other accounts of the happenings, they do in fact seem much more consistent with what has been termed "poltergeist" phenomena.  Usually a young teen is at the center of the activities.  Consciously, they are not aware of what they're doing.  A lot of very unusual happenings tend to occur, although they are generally not life-threatening or severely injurious.  In this case, we do in fact have an early-teen girl at the center of things.  On at least one occasion, she was filmed deliberately causing some of the phenomena that were being attributed to an unseen entity.  This in itself wouldn't necessarily mean that everything which happened could be so easily explained, but certainly strengthened the hands of skeptics who think the whole thing must have been a hoax.  More to the point of this movie: apparently the Warrens were involved for the sum total of one day!  They were "disinvited" when, reportedly, Ed Warren made a comment to the effect that "a lot of money could be made" by investigating what was going on.

The bottom line is: if you just want a good, scary story this might not scare you as much as you hoped.  It does have a few startling or briefly scary scenes, but for the most part it's predictable and simultaneously incredible.  On the other hand if you're looking for a good "true" story of a haunting or something like that, this seems to be so far from the real story that it is best viewed as pure fiction.  I came away from this significantly less impressed with the factual underpinnings of the tale than I did with the original "Conjuring" [and by the way, "conjuring" itself is a bit misguided for what these films seem to be aiming for, since it's more suggestive of a magician's act than of a demonic possession].

Well there it is.  Many will like it, despite what I personally see as weaknesses.  In general the acting is decent, even if the story is far less "based on real events" than it would have you believe.

Oh wow!  The Conjuring 2 is a tremendous horror.  I can't recall the first one very well at the moment.  Even though it was released only a few years ago, I can't remember much about it I'm afraid.  This means the opening segment with the seance... I'm not entirely sure if this particular scene reveals how the first Conjuring movie ended.  However you do NOT need to see the first Conjuring to enjoy part 2.  I love this movie to pieces man!

I have to say I absolutely love this seance scene.  I love how it was made from both a writing and cinematic point of view.  It's based on Vera and her husband's previous paranormal case in either the first Conjuring or a separate incident.  We see ghost investigator Vera Farmiga close her eyes, and a moment later her brain allows her body to transport to other rooms of the house witnessing terrifying evil roaming around.  When she travels to the basement and sees ghostly children, well that's terrifying enough.  But when she looks in a mirror, sees the ghosts behind her getting more numerous/more evil, turns around to see nothing there... only for a ghost woman to appear RIGHT in front of her when she tries to glance into the mirror again?  Oh man that's scary!

But you see, what makes the Conjuring 2 so great is that it often toys with your emotions.  Sometimes you'll witness a terrifying demonic encounter, but other times it's just atmosphere that leads to nothing or makes your eyes play tricks with your head.  That itself would be impressive, but you know the Conjuring 2 kicks up the storytelling even further.  Let me explain.

The story is about Vera Farmiga and her husband (played by Patrick Wilson, the same two actors from the first Conjuring).  They visit a small town in England to help a family (a mother, 3 sisters and a brother) after two of the sisters experiment with a ouija board.  Turns out a demon has a particular interest in the one sister, Madison Wolf's character.  Throughout the movie we see Exorcist-like moments when her voice turns demonic, the tone in the room becomes dreadful, lights flicker, and a burst of sinister energy is released in some way.

The family contact Vera and Patrick as a last resort.  Locally they bring over news reporters and another paranormal investigator (Simon McBurney's character).  The news reporter suspects the daughter might be faking the whole thing.  This aspect of the story continues later on which I'll mention below.

At first the mother (Frances O' Connor's character) thinks the kids are just trying to spook each other with little games when she discovers the ouija board tucked under the one daughter's bed... but then a moment later the dresser in the bedroom slides across the floor and slams into the wall prompting the entire family to leave their home and run across the street to their neighbors house terrified for their lives.

Soon enough we see several unforgettable moments on a smaller scale.  Perhaps these could be considered teasers since the story likes to unfold gradually to successfully get viewers to absorb a little bit of fear at a time before eventually going all in and scaring the wits out of you.  How about this one.  Madison wakes up, sits up in her bed, has a conversation with something her sister (played by Lauren Esposito) sleeping in the bed next to her can't see, and assumes Madison's talking in her sleep.  Then when Lauren goes back to sleep suddenly Madison is standing RIGHT in front of her and talking.  Lauren is confused and upset... until she hears the demonic voice "This is my house!" behind her.  This prompts the sisters to run to their mom's bedroom terrified.  Awesome stuff!

How about the little firetruck toy the little boy plays with (Benjamin Haigh) in front of a tent in the upstairs hallway?  The atmosphere here is done tremendously.  As the boy walks to his bedroom he hears the siren on the truck turn on as it moves across the floor.  Scared, he heads to his bedroom.  He continues to peek behind the hallway to make sure the truck isn't moving.  You know how a little kid's imagination can be- when something odd happens a kid might get concerned and think it's a ghost, encouraging the kid to keep a close eye on the object in question.  When the firetruck rolls down the hallway and gets his attention, he jumps out of bed.  He walks down the hallway and glances inside the tent to see something demonic.  To his mom's bedroom he runs!

My goodness, there's so many scary scenes.  Too many to mention!  These ones are legitimately awesome.  The Conjuring 2 really feels like a true horror film to me.  How about the moment when Madison's attached to the living room ceiling and watches the ghostly presence of an older man below jump off the chair, walk up the stairs and into the sister's bedroom?  Since Madison's stuck on the ceiling during this scene she can't free herself, so she's forced to feel the floor boards above shake!  A moment later she morphs up inside the bedroom and sits on the floor.  Little moments like these are absolutely terrifying to me.  Proof that ghosts and demons are scarier than anything else I can think of (at least, according to me- it's a matter of debate of course!)  It should be mentioned the rocking chair is the main source of all evil.  This is why Madison encounters things in this spot of the house more than anywhere else.  And yes, you know it- that chair's going to rock in the middle of the night!

How about the other moment that nearly made me poop myself?  When the brother walks across the hallway inside the neighbors house and hears a bell ringing.  They own a rottweiler and the dog likes to smack the bell with his nose or paw whenever he wants outside.  The boy assumes the dog is ringing the bell... but instead we see the dog morph into an extremely tall demonic figure and chase the frightened little boy back to his parents and siblings in the living room.  They all see a tall shadow coming down the hallway... only for it to be Madison Wolfe's character.  This poor girl is being tormented by this demon time and time again.  The way this figure branches out and grows tall right next to the boy is truly scary.

I badly want to mention the TV remote incident early on when the demonic incidents first begin and the scene with Patrick fixing a washing machine leak (wow, more like a flood!) in the basement only for a figure to rise from the water and cause harm, but I won't.  Remember when I said the Conjuring 2 kicks up the storytelling a lot more compared to most horrors?  Let me elaborate on that.  First of all this is supposedly based on a true story that took place in the late 70's which is why we hear the Clash, the Hollies and other bands (then again the Hollies "Bus Stop" is more suitable for a 60's tune but who cares, it's a great song!)

The way these events are told... eventually things don't add up according to the investigators.  It appears Madison Wolf is faking everything.  At least, everyone except Patrick and Vera have concluded the poor girl might be faking the entire possession.  I had to sit on my couch and think about this from the accusers point of view.  Even if she was faking, how can you explain a little girls voice suddenly turning demonic?  I mean it sounds *truly* demonic- not a little girl imitating a demonic voice.  The investigators should have caught onto this.  Also the bite marks on the girls neck... pretty sure poor Madison couldn't have bitten herself, and the mouth was too big for one of her sisters or brothers to have done it.  Investigation 101 guys.

This prompts Patrick, Vera, Simon and everyone else to leave the house after uncomfortably concluding Madison's been faking the entire incident (with their supposed video tape proof showing Madison throwing objects around in the kitchen).  There was also a seance that took place in the living room.  Madison reveals the demon won't make an appearance if the investigators are looking directly at her, so they turn around and ask questions.  AWESOME moment here- while they turn away you can see through the blurriness that Madison's body shape changes into a demon.  Similar to the rottweiler moment I mention above (except in the rottweiler scene, the dog changes shape in the darkness).

Anyway while this seance is going on, the investigators ask Madison to place water in her mouth to prove she's not speaking.  This seance occurs way before anyone suspected the girl might be faking.  Later on when the investigation team suspect she's faking the whole thing, they think she simply spit the water into the cup while their backs were turned, then took another sip when they turned around.  This is not the case though.  Before Patrick and Vera travel too far on the train and leave the country, they head back when they realize they've made a big mistake.  Also this is a SPOILER, but the supposed demon isn't as frightening as one would expect.  There's a reason why, and it's because he himself (the ghost of Bill Wilkins- the man who used to live in the house) is actually being controlled by a demon.  The demon says his name is Bill Wilkins. Bill's ghost is being controlled by an evil presence.

But wow is this movie awesome!  I never even mentioned Vera and her daughter are being haunted by their own black cloak-wearing beady eyed demon at home.  Her daughter feels the presence of a dark figure walking down the hallway while the two are relaxing in the living room.  Vera tells her daughter to hide in the room after they both terrifyingly see the dark figure standing at the end of the hallway.  Vera chases after the demon.  When she enters the room where the demon went, we see this portrait Patrick made (I think from a dream he had) that shows the same beady eyed demon that's now in the room somewhere.  I'm not sure if it's hilarious or scary that Vera sees the shadow of this demon walk across the wall, enter the picture frame from inside the wall, line up his body where his face would be, take his hands out from behind the wall, grab the picture frame, pull it off and literally RUN towards Vera pushing her into the back room.  This scene is almost hilarious even if it's not supposed to be.

Otherwise the Conjuring 2 excels as a really good horror movie.  Perhaps Patrick's character being a fixer upper around the house in England fixing plumbing issues, and picking up a guitar to sing Elvis tunes as a way to entertain the kids is a bit much though.  These scenes felt silly to me.  Then again they also serve as temporary relief from all the horrific events going on.  Then again, hey, these moments just add to the close relationship between Vera and Patrick, and add more to their side of the story (they didn't really want to investigate anymore homes- they were dragged into this incident in England in fact).

No complaints with this movie folks.  None at all!  Okay just one!  Elvis Presley's "I Can't Help Falling In Love With You" is way out of place.  Patrick singing this song to the kids is almost hilarious.  It would be like playing Black Sabbath's "War Pigs" at a little kid's birthday party.  Yeah, really out of place.  Highly recommended.

I'm a big fan of James Wan and the first Conjuring was awesome! So needless to say I was beside myself when I heard they were coming out with a second conjuring movie. Wow...kind of disappointed in the outcome. The movie had a great premise. The English setting was a nice change of pace. The cast was chosen perfectly with some new faces in the mix. The chills and scary moments were typical James Wan and done very well. Then by the second act, it all fell apart. The story became to convoluted, the scary moments more weird than scary (the crooked man was laughable with the strange clay-mation style effects) and the overall spookiness of the movie dwindled into a terrible episode of the X-Files. What happened to this movie? It had so much advertisement and hype when it first came out. The trailers were all over YouTube and it actually looked like a good movie.
I gave it three stars because it did have some good scenes that legit scared the crap out of me. And because Ed and Lorraine Warren and the story they told was awesome. But the ending made me feel disappointed and let down. I won't give away the ending but it left much to be desired. If they do a Conjuring 3 I hope they put much more effort into the story than they did the second one. I don't know, watch the second film and find out for yourself.

An engaging human interest story in addition to an above-average demon possession tale - albeit still "Hollywood-ized". Screenplays for Conjuring 1 and 2 are based on case files of Ed & Lorraine Warren, world renowned demonologists, who often worked in cooperation with the Vatican and specially-trained priests beginning in the 1970's. With this sequel and the first Conjuring flick, it's also gratifying to see the comeback of Jesus Christ as the ultimate exorcist of demons in human beings. Lorraine even reads her Bible for spiritual re fortification. How often do you see that in movies or television? For a few decades, it seemed like there was no force greater than Satan in movies. While that may remain true in some studios, it has never been the case in the greater community of Christian faith. It's unusual for me to review and recommend a "horror movie" but as I said, it's not typical -- this one has more spiritual substance to it, and amazingly, the sequel is better than the first Conjuring. The acting is superb with the child actors being just as believable, if not more, than the adults. The cinematography, CGI and editing are top notch. I was impressed, and will most definitely watch these again while anticipating the release of Conjuring 3.

Everything that was done right in The Conjuring is done equally well or better in The Conjuring 2, with paranormal investigators Ed and Lorraine Warren (Patrick Wilson and Vera Faramiga) heading this time to England to investigate a case that would become known as the Enfield Haunting.  A newly single mother and her four children are the targets of malevolent entities, possibly attracted to the stress the family was under due to the recent seperation from the father.  Having such a mundane possible explanation floated as the genesis for the haunting may come off as bland to some, but I found it gave an eerie feel of authenticity to the film; it's like it was so plain no one would make it up.  Whatever originally initiated the haunting though, it soon goes from bad to worse and becomes a real threat to the people involved.  The Conjuring 2 is scarier than its predecessor and also excels in charaterization and overall production, with a great musical score by Joseph Bishara (who also did the music for the first Conjuring and Annabelle as well as for the Insidious movies).  Another thing of note is that the movie follows up on the plot thread from the original movie about an exorcism the Warrens were involved in prior to the main story in The Conjuring 1.  In this exorcism, the possessed man said or showed something to Lorraine that scared her so badly that she nearly quit.  That gets explained and followed up on in here.  I could go on with superlatives like 'excellent' and 'intense', but the bottom line is just that The Conjuring 2 is one of the best movies of the year and a must-see for anyone who liked the first Conjuring and Annabelle even a little bit, or for horror fans in general. I'm not a movie critic - but I respectfully feel "The Conjuring" is a much more terrifying movie than its sequel.

I suppose what drew me to The Conjuring (as a series) was this sort of balance between "believability" and "supernatural." In The Conjuring it wasn't THAT big of a stretch - you have an evil entity that is largely undetectable outside of the various "happenings" that plague the family. You don't *really* see the entity until the end save a couple quick glimpses. Loose ends are tied up.

BUT, I digress, this is a review of "The Conjuring 2."

SPOILERS AHEAD

This movie is awash in opacity - we see the evil entities nearly from the beginning. That includes the old man, the nun, and the slender-esque creature. I'm not afraid - I'm not able to be afraid - I've SEEN the adversary. That takes the suspense out of this movie for me. The "fear factor" for me is the "unknown" property of the evil entities. Please see my above reference to the first "The Conjuring." The supernatural element is NOT subtle - it's TOO obvious. We visit the case of the Italian man who was able "to speak Latin backwards" and it's here we are introduced to the Nun. And, figures, Ed paints a picture of this entity. Great, no mystery.

I'm trying to make this short. So my other issue is the conclusion. Where did the Nun come from? I KNOW she came from Lorraine's dream - but WHY? We should ground the Nun better in some element of reality beyond a "dream/vision/premonition." She is defeated...and that's that. No exposition. What happens to the "old man"? The evil "puppet" - did he go to heaven? No? Dissipate? Go to hell?

Give me an ending, movie. Certain ends have to be tied. Not all of them! Not necessarily at least. But *some* have to be to deliver some element of satisfaction. This would be forgivable if this was a cliffhanger to a third movie - but the reality is - it's not.

Whether you believe the events are true or not, this movie is a scary one.

Based on a paranormal investigation in England, it features the psychic investigators from "The Conjuring" this time as the main characters.

After being accused on a TV talk show of being fakes, Lorraine Warren decides to stop delving into the actual psychic end of the paranormal but simply do investigations.  The fact that during their study of the Amityville house, she had a vision of her husband's death, aids her decision. Then, their pastor asks them to go to England and determine the veracity of a "haunting..."

Cliches are present, to be sure, but also some twists here and there, such as putting the investigators in a certain amount of jeopardy. There are plenty of shock moments in this...and a few where you'd expect them and they don't appear, making the tension even more so. It's chills a-plenty, with the creepiness making this a good Halloween film.  It's also the kind I'd suggest you not watch alone or late at night.  I did both, and I'm not ashamed to admit it...I stopped a quarter way into the movie, and finished the next morning in broad daylight.  Laugh if you will...watching this and listening to a house creak and groan around and various electrical appliances rattle and groan you can do things to the most steadfast imagination!

The child actress playing the girl at the center of the investigation is great as a frightened child who isn't believes and someone brave enough to persevere with the Warrens' encouragement.

This was such a good film, I find myself wondering if there will be a Conjuring 3 and actually looking forward to it if there is.

They are well known charlatans and I couldn't care less about the supposed true events that these movies supposedly portray. I get into these movies simply for the entertainment value. And I really like the actors playing the Warren's, they're really likeable, I just don't believe anything in terms of real events.

Several people in the theater were laughing right from the opening and that's never a good thing in a horror movie. I will admit that as far as jump scares go, these are top notch. The Conjuring 2 has some very effective scares, I just wish it showed more restraint like the original. I also didn't care for some of the creature/ghost designs. The Crooked Man wasn't really working due to the phony CGI. Several other things I could nitpick as well but I'll just once again point to my previous complaint- this movie was just too cheesy and cartoony for my tastes, and I'll pretty much leave it at that. Although the scene in the basement where he surprises them is quite scary. By the way, what is the deal with their flooded basement? There is basically a lake under their home.

All in all, if you enjoyed the first movie, no reason you won't like this one. It's a very worthy follow-up. Also, in case you are wondering, you absolutely don't need to have seen the first movie to understand everything in this one. You are just missing some backstory on the main characters, which isn't necessary here.

I'm a huge fan of horror movies, stories, and tales. I purchased the first Conjuring movie and I was a little bit disappointed because I did not find it creepy nor scary. I was waiting for the Conjuring 2 movie to come out on Prime Video. However, after reading all of the positive reviews regarding the Conjuring 2 movie; I made the choice to purchase it. I'm actually glad I did not wait. A lot of the reviews have already went into the plot of the story (which I think can be a bit of a spoiler for people who have not viewed the movie) so I will not go into the plot. I will state that this movie is scarier than all the Amityville horror movies combined. Think of the original Exorcist movie and this movie kind of piggybacks around that theme. It does have a slow buildup however, the middle and end results are perfect. It's a perfect sequel (usually sequels are not that scary). One of the points that make this movie so visually scary and entertaining; is the fact that it is told from a child's point of view. I enjoyed watching a little bit of the Warren's family story. I love the fact that some portions of this movie were based on a true story as well. When the old man showed his face quickly (from behind the television screen) I thought I was going to wet my pants. Small parts of the movie were actually touching (I will never forget how this movie introduced me to the beautiful song "Falling in Love With You"). Overall, it's a perfect Halloween treat for any horror movie fan. There are no graphic sex scenes, blood, or gore. It's just an entertaining, old school setting, with a well-rounded cast movie. I recommend this movie.

Vera Farmiga and Patrick Wilson are excellent to their roles. "The Conjuring 2" is an excellent example of what more sequels should aspire to be. It takes viewers to a thrilling ride that keeps you on the edge. It is a perfectly executed haunting movie from James Wan that dives deep below the surface to explore themes of vision, belief and faith, and the family drama is still at the center and is quite effective. Can't wait for the next one!

Exactly as my star rating says, I say, "Eh, it's okay." "The Conjuring 2" is not horrible, but, like the first in the series, it still tries far too hard to be "The Exorcist". It doesn't help that I no longer believe in the polarized, black-and-white "there is always a solid good and a solid evil" dichotomy that these films always rely on to thrill the culture that was either raised in church for whom the psychological sinews of that may still hold on tight or they still go and wholeheartedly believe all of it for reasons I will never understand. I do give it props for one scene involving a very tall being that would've made Tim Burton smile, that was a little more original for the "haunted house" genre. Anymore I tend to prefer psychological thrillers, slasher films, or something like "The Witch" that relies 99% on atmosphere instead of the emotionally fleeting jump scares.

I love to watch Vera Farmiga and Patrick Wilson as real life demonologist couple Ed and Lorraine Warren!  They play Roman Catholic demonologists in both this movie and the first Conjuring movie.  This couple was involved in the famous Amityville horror investigation as well as numerous other documented and well-known paranormal cases. Much of their work was done as agents of the Roman Catholic Church.  Ed Warren was the only exorcist to ever be sanctioned by the Catholic Church that was not a member of the clergy.  Lorraine Warren worked as a sensitive and medium for her entire career again with the blessing of the Catholic Church. Both of these things are highly unusual and lend credence  authenticity to thier story.  Although they investigated well over 10,000 cases they say only a small percentage were actually paranormal in nature. I genuinely wish they had come up with better titles for these movies because they are based on a real couple and their real cases making these movies more than just "jump and scare" flicks. These movies are different than your typical horror films. They are far more interesting in storyline and are laced with compassion.  The starring couple genuinely wants to help the families in the movies giving the movie more depth and realness than your typical horror film.  I preferred the first movie to the second but really enjoyed seeing more from this couple's case history.  I really hope they make another one! I would absolutely recommend it, it's a lot of fun!

Must admit it takes an awful lot to unnerve me these days, guess i've seen far too many chillers down the years
for them to have much effect these days....having said that the chilling fact of films such as this is that they are
based on documented evidence of the events....which for me is what makes tje film worth viewing.
Set in the mid-to-late 1970's -
'Patrick Wilson' and 'Vera Farmiga' reprise their roles as paranormal investigators 'Ed and Lorraine Warren'
After investigating whether a demonic presence had been involved in the Amitytiville Killings, 'Ed and Lorraine'
one year on are asked to fly to London to investigate strange occurrences that had befallen the 'Hodgson' house-
hold in Enfield where 11 year old Janet had been experiencing disturbing happenings which had also began to
affect the others living in the house, so much so they had become too scared to stay there.
'Ed and Lorraine' have to determine whether what appears to be possessing 'Janet' is a genuine happening, the
signs are that they are....though a fellow investigator has doubts....to refer it on, the two have to be convinced it
is not an elaborate hoax.....when 'Janet' is filmed deliberately throwing furniture and crockery about in the kitchen
it seems that it's game-over.....however whilst planning to go back to the States 'Ed' has to clarify something that was
troubling him which leads to he and 'Lorraine' returning to Enfield....it was as well they did.
Though i didn't really find the film to be scary it's easy to see how some of the images would be to many....the fact
it is based on a real happening is why, for me, it's worthy of a viewing.
Makes one wonder that's for sure ...

James Wan has proven himself to be arguably the greatest horror director of his generation. To be able to make a sequel to one of the greatest horror movies of the 21st century (so far) and make it AS good, if not in some cases better than the original, is just about as impressive a feat that exists in filmmaking. It is all too rare these days to get a genre film with the level of quality that Wan has been able to deliver here yet again.

Because we know that Ed & Lorraine Warren are/were real people, and that this is once again another 'true' story of theirs, the feeling you get when you watch these films is different. Beyond just making a sincerely effective fright flick, James Wan also made an excellent period piece. The classic film grain look as well as the color grading, great costumes and era relevant music and cars nailed the feeling of 1977.

Overall the greatest thing about this movie is that, like it's predecessor, it is nothing like 90%+ of the 'scary' movies that come out today. This is not a cheap, jump scare, chair jumper movie. It is a genuine horror movie that was designed to terrify you, over and over and over. Without sounding blasphemous, Wan is doing with horror for us the same thing Friedkin did for The Exorcist and Kubrick did for The Shining. Appreciate the quality of this film.

Holy moly. Scary movies have fallen very short lately (at least true horror movies that aren't just full of gore) and have a track record of being very disappointing, so it's rare to come across one that both genuinely scares people while actually being good. I watched this with this hubby, who makes a point to never jump or show that he's scared and laughs at those who do, with the lights on. Within the first 5 minutes we both had jumped and I had about 4 heart attacks.

The movie follows the TRUE STORY of a recently divorced mother with 4 children in England who experience an insane paranormal ordeal. They experience activity ranging anywhere from shadows to furniture thrown across the room and appearances/possessions by more than one demon. What I loved was that these activities didn't just occur to only the family, it happened in front of policemen and neighbors and investigators as well, making it way more realistic and frightening. It wasn't one of those things where you find yourself screaming at the TV for them to just get out of the house, because they do at one point and it follows them there too, knowing no bounds. They seem to touch on almost every type of fear relating to paranormal things so it was well ranged...a critic might say it had too many elements but I thought that was kind of genius because it will reach into a wider range of fears that people harbor. At one point they bring out The Crooked Man, I'll admit his animation wasn't great but still scared the wits out of me due to my fear of unnatural body movement and overly tall, thin people.

Most horror films these days concentrate more on being gory, gross or putting together a really cool creature or corpse that skin comes off when a character touches it or something special effects makeup wise. There's of course your slasher films that have been the most successful of the horror film. Nothing wrong with any of those things, I love those films too, but you hardly ever come across big budget horror movies these days that are designed to be scary. Conjuring 2 does this though. Sure it's predictable, and likely has very little to do with the "true story" it is loosely based on, but these things don't really matter when you've been entertained for over two hours, with something going on all the time. Madison Wolfe does a brilliant job as Janet the most targeted for torment child of the family by what's in the house. The acting for the Janet character would have either made this a great film or a terrible one. If horror films were taken more seriously by award bodies, Wolfe would certainly be up for best actor awards for this. Vera Farmiga (Bates Motel) and Patrick Wilson again do a great job as The Warrens.

Like most haunted house films of course you wonder why the first time the family knows for sure there's something there they don't just cut their financial losses, walk out the door and not come back. But you wouldn't have a movie if that happened. In the deleted scenes (found on region 4 DVD) there is a scene where they do address this sort of, where they decide if it didn't leave Janet alone when she stayed with the Nottingham's, it's likely to follow her wherever she goes so they might as well deal with it in the house. There are decisions that characters make like in any horror film where you scream at the screen why would you do that? But again this is a staple of horror films.

Very few sequels surpass the original in their entertainment factor. Especially horror movies, where most sequels are let's face it, pretty terrible. The Conjuring 2 however is more than worth your time checking out.

Its no secret that James Wan only makes horror classics, and this is his latest masterpiece. Despite the deceptively clich premise, the film is a funhouse of fear, using all sorts of perfectly executed scares to keep viewers on edge. The director just understands the typical rhythms and beats of the genre so well, that he knows exactly how to maximize the fright in every sequence with precise and off-kilter timing. The plot has a variety of novel inventions too which subvert traditional expectations and tropes, making this a further evolution of the haunted house/possession genre.

But beyond the filmmaking, the plotting is smart too, patiently marrying disparate subplots into one big, cohesive finish. The main characters may appear kinda square, but they have an earnest strength that makes them admirably cool. From the light touches of humor, the flawless period production design, to the familys heartfelt emotional struggles, this is a well-made movie by any metric. But as its first function is fear, it particularly excels in that regard like few horror films ever do.

This stuff is getting pretty formulaic. I wanted to like this film. I really did. I can even appreciate the idea of "exaggerating" a true story a bit for the sake of entertainment. What I can never forgive however, is the bald, finger-pointing-in-your-face, mawkish, bible-humping, overwrought proselytizing that this film absolutely reeks of. What I'm speaking of specifically are the countless needless digressions alluding to the relationship between Ed and Lorraine and their endless, embarrassingly deadpan, discussions about the precise ins and outs of "demon" hunting. I get it already. They're a down-home, family-values, guitar-strummin' happy American couple. That would be fine if this wasn't supposed to be a horror film. But after a while, it literally sucked (and I do mean sucked) so much of the entertainment out of the film that by the time the scares reappeared, I needed my hand to support to my chin to keep from falling over with abject boredom. The first one was definitely better. The digressions were fewer. The "family" moments were brief, generalizable to a wider audience, and meaningful. Most importantly, they didn't take away from the general aura of misgiving because the proselytizing was far, far less prominent. What I really don't understand is what exactly James Wan is expecting us to derive from all this. What I understand even less, is how audiences that aren't American can relate to any of this. It must be a terrible disappointment to see the value of enterntainment being slowly  replaced by the odiously conspicuous urge to "convert" audiences over to some horribly narrow viewpont that only a comparatively small demographic can relate to. What a pathetic substitute. I think I'm done with James Wan at this point. Maybe Ty West will start to get a little better. He certainly couldn't do worse than this.

James Wan is probably the biggest name in horror right now, every big movie has his name attached to it, and for the most part, he hasn't missed a beat. I liked Insidious, i felt it was a bit too crazy, but it was engaging, i absolutely loved The Conjuring and the original Saw is a classic in my opinion. The Conjuring is his most frightening and well made film, and the sequel expands on it infinitely. Back are the well written and acted characters, the engaging story, the genuine emotion, but with a more claustrophobic environment. While i didn't find it AS scary as the first, The Conjuring 2 brings back the same formula of holding back on jumpscares, letting you take in the almost unbearable tension, builidng up to nothing or something unsettling. This style of horror may be a huge turn off for a lot of viewers expecting to jump out of their seats, but for someone who wants to literally cringe from the anxiety and fear, this is the perfect movie. I hope this franchise continues under James Wan and stays this consistent. The spin offs on the other hand....

Horror meister James Wan, creator of the seven-film Saw nightmare, worked hard to escape the sequel curse in the follow-on to his well-reviewed 2013 demonic shocker, The Conjuring. And it shows.

The Conjuring 2 is a complicated, multi-segmented narrative that's much longer, more elaborate, more dramatic, and more packed with chilling moments and hair-raising visuals than one could anticipate, even from Wan.

Returning stars Vera Farmiga and Patrick Wilson act their hearts out as real-life ghost-and-ghoul hunters Lorraine and Ed Warren.

The film, a horror flick with the chutzpah to run 133 minutes, tries at real emotional depth and complex plotting. It tries, in other words, to reach epic status.

Does it succeed? Eh, I guess so. There's a lot more here than in the first film, but it doesn't feel quite as exciting.

A postmodern American Gothic bouillabaisse, The Conjuring 2 opens with what seems to be a sequel to The Amityville Horror, with the Warrens investigating the house made famous by a half-dozen films, including Stuart Rosenberg's 1979 classic.

Just as we're settling down into the story, the scene changes, and the Warrens are off to England and another famous case, the Enfield Haunting, also the subject of books and flicks.

But Wan's film isn't merely a meta tourist jaunt through horror movie history. Once it takes root in England, it blossoms into a full-blooded thriller.

Wan pulls out all the stops - does he ever - as he takes us through a warped story about a working-class single mum, Peggy Hodgson (Frances O'Connor), whose life is turned inside out by an evil apparition that takes up residence in Peggy's preteen daughter, Janet (Madison Wolfe).

I sometimes confuse the Conjuring pics with the Insidious franchise of demon-infestation flicks, which features Lin Shaye as a very Lorraine Warren-like psychic and ghoul-exterminator.

Wan's films, however, have heart. Maybe even a soul.

The Enfield Poltergeist was a Hoax, and a well documented one at that, which the Warrens had very little to do with, but of course every case the Warrens were involved with somehow became demonic possessions or one form or another.  I see studio wrangled the surviving family members to step up for promotional spots too.  I'm sure they were paid well...

The movie is entertaining, but is mostly made up nonsense when it comes to the Warrens.  If you like scary movies, and I count myself in that group, then it's a fun movie which I enjoyed.  It gave me the chills more than once. However it needs to be said that the Warrens are well known charlatans who (Especially the late Ed Warren) just wanted to make a quick buck.  Funny how they documented all these strange goings on through the years (With Audio and Video supposedly) yet there has been precious little of that supposed evidence released to the public. I wonder why??

One of the investigators of the Enfield case had this to say about Ed Warren: "All I can remember is Ed Warren telling me that he could make a lot of money for me out of it. So I thought, 'Well that's all I need to know from you' and I got myself out of his way as soon as I could.' "

I'm sure there will be a Conjuring 3 with more made up non-sense about how the Warrens were heroes, and I'll probably watch that too. Can take some solace in Ed is dead and unable to partake in the new found fame.  Lorraine is probably laughing all the way to the bank.

There have been a lot of reviews praising The Conjuring 2 (TC2) as superior than the original, and while I don't disagree, I believe some of the thematic elements remain the same. Perhaps the distinguishing factor that propels this one above its predecessor has more to do with the on-screen chemistry between Vera Farmiga & Patrick Wilson. Portraying real life Ed & Lorraine Warren, there is a magnetic and deep sense of love they offer one another rooted in things a relationship between two people calls for such as guidance, patience and strength in the face of adversity. In this sequel, it simply feels like both Farmiga & Wilson have reached a better understanding of their personas as well as their interaction with one another.

Assuming you had seen the first one, youll remember that Farmigas character uses visions to help clear the path of demonic forces that conspire against humankind. One of her visions disturbed her to the point where she decided to put an end to the work that she and her husband (Wilson) had been doing and yet the inherent struggle to stand by while others are in need propels the would-be demonologists to take on another case and assist an English family nonetheless. Such is the premise for this extremely well produced film by James Wan.

It seems like the horror genre is robust enough to be further divided into subdivisions such as slasher flicks, gore-fests, psychological thrillers and supernatural sagas which is why recommending a film under the huge umbrella of Horror is not such a great idea at times.  While the audiences for Cannibal Holocaust, Scream, Saw and Silence of the Lambs may be vastly different, a film that encompasses traits from these different sub-divisions is hard to come by. If there is one film that stands alone in this distinction, it would have to be the film The Exorcist, hands down. While CJ2 is no Exorcist, it accomplishes what it sets out to do quite effectively borrowing components without compromising its core - what goes bump in the night?

The cinematographer and supporting cast do a fine job of setting up scares and even though you may think you know how the filmmaker will take you to a scare, its really the combination of all the elements (lets not forget the sound, music and film editing) working in tandem that will creep you out. The director uses all the essentials to deliver an experience that does not talk down to audiences or treats them like idiots but rather tells of his love of cinema.

Bottom line: Incidentally, I watched this on Amazon, so Im not able to speak to the quality/purpose of extra features on the disc. I do recommend setting aside the need to draw a comparison to the first film and allowing the material from this film draw you into the atmospheric world of the Warrens. Some audience members may delight in the knowledge that this film is based on one of the Warrens case files. However, one may watch this film without realizing this aspect and instead concede that the real driving force of the film is regarding the balance that Lorraine Warren struggles to keep in helping others versus a loss at her great, personal expense. There is an underlying theme that the potential for human suffering and loss of life at the hands of malicious beings is truly the scariest thing of all. To quote Edmund Burke, The only thing necessary for the triumph of evil is for good men to do nothing.  Excellent, A-

At times this movie showed signs of its predecessor in producing some real scares, like anticipating the awakening of a child due to a "visitor" in the bedroom, or experiencing the simple creepiness of some lone sole going down in a dark basement to follow a faint noise.  But, aside from that, "Conjuring 2" just did not live up to the drama and scares that came with the first film.  I believe part of that was due to a disjointed plot whose base is divided between America and England, but also perhaps because the infestation of evil into a home with four kids was done very well in the first, and is a bit "old school" in this follow-up.  It's still better viewing than a lot of other movies that came out at the same time, and the actors who play the Warrens are always pretty much on the mark and quite believable.  Still worth an On-Demand showing for a rainy afternoon.

A co-worker knows I enjoy horror, and told me to watch The Enfield Haunting on Hulu. I never got around to it, so when The Conjuring 2 came out, and I saw that it was about the same hauntings in England, I was optimistic that this would be good. Unfortunately, for me, it was just okay.

I thought I had watched the first Conjuring, but couldn't remember anything about it. So thats never a good sign. I should have thought about this before watching the second one. There was nothing wrong with the movie, it just did nothing for me.

Spoilers Ahead, although not really because what Im going to talk about happens early on in the movie, and its just going to be vague.

The evil looking nun was there for jump scares, and to highlight the Church and that the Warrens need to defer to it when getting involved in these cases. I really didn't see what else she was needed for.

The old man in the chair was a bit creepy. Even before the hauntings began though, I would have put the chair to the curb, and painted the wall behind it, since both were disgusting.

The relationship that the Warrens had with each other was nice, and I believed the love that they felt for each other. And it amused me that they just leave their daughter when they go on these long trips. Where is she? By herself at home, with a relative. To me the daughter seemed like an afterthought.

If you are really into movies about hauntings I would say give this one a watch, but otherwise skip it.

This is one of the rare films where I feel it surpasses the original. The conjuring 2 takes what worked in the original & builds upon it. James Wan once again shows why he's one of the best modern horror directors. The films is creepy, chilling & very atmospheric. The cast once again do a very good job especially Vera Farmiga & Patrick Wilson who once again do a great job playing Ed & Lorraine Warren. The basic plot is based on the Enfield Poltergeist case & includes other things I don't want to ruin for anyone who hasn't seen the film yet. The setting, mood, music, tension all come together to create what is the horror film of the year. If you liked the first Conjuring film, haunted house films or just horror films in general then its very easy to recommend The Conjuring 2. When watch on a quite, dark night it will have you checking the shadows. The features on the disc include behind the scenes, a featurette on the real life Enfield Poltergeist case, interviews, & how certain effects were done. Don't miss out on this film, its one of most well made horror films ive seen in awhile.

The Conjuring 2 is a sequel to the 2013 box office hit. This time, paranormal investigators Ed and Lorraine Warren (Patrick Wilson, Vera Farmiga) look into Englands Enfield haunting, a notorious 1977 case involving single mother Penny Hodgson (Frances OConnor), her four children, and an entity that targets her 11-year-old daughter, Janet (Madison Wolfe). The previous owner of their home, 72-year-old Bill Wilkins (Bob Adrian), died in his favorite chair and his spirit refuses to leave, repeating again and again, This is my home!

Like the first film, the sequel intelligently and methodically tracks the Warrens as they carry out an investigation. Scientific and level-headed, they go about their work seriously, knowing their very presence can escalate danger to their clients and themselves. A horror film is helped considerably when its protagonists are not hormone-driven teenagers or people who do exactly the opposite of what rational human beings would do when encountering peril. Though horror fans might become impatient with scenes underscoring the affection between Ed and Lorraine, they do provide some depth of characterization so that the audience regards them as real people and not merely the means to elicit scares.

Director James Wan provides plenty of jump scares as well as suspenseful, eerie moments that create tension as the couple pursue their investigation. The cinematography features several sweeping wide-angle establishing shots and uninterrupted takes during the demonic possession scenes, which give the sense that we, the viewers, are participants. The movie leaves us wondering whether the events are real or an elaborate hoax, leaving open to interpretation why the Warrens have taken on such an unorthodox pursuit.

Bonus extras on the Blu-ray release include deleted scenes and the featurettes The Enfield Poltergeist: Living the Horror and Crafting The Conjuring 2.

I rented this last night and I am very impressed, almost blown away. You've got to understand though that I've been watching these movies for so long that I'm usually desensitized. I am a huge fan of Ed and Lorraine Warren and their work/contributions to the paranormal world are invaluable and immeasurable. Needless to say, I've gone to see every film based upon their careers. The Conjuring 2 regards the Enfield Portergeist case, and the movie loosely follows the events that occurred to those involved. Having read in-depth about that case/watched documentaries/other footage, I was well-versed going into this movie. The first half of the film follows the case details almost to the letter but as the film progresses, Hollywood takes over. In my opinion, the true case details are more terrifying than what the film suggested. With that being said, I still recommend this movie version as it is scary, with excellent build-ups and pacing throughout (and it does shed light onto true accounts of paranormal and demonic experiences). If it helps the reader, I consider it almost as good as the first Conjuring and all in all, it does make into my top 10 favorite horror films.

After everything weve seen there isn't much that rattles either of us anymore, but this one, this one still haunts me. After investigating the possession of the Amityville house affects their lives in ways they cant shake Ed (Wilson) and Lorraine (Farmiga) Warren decide to end their career of investigation. After a similar event happens in England the church asks them to travel to the house and decide if the church should get involved. What they find is more terrifying than either has experienced but are struggling to find proof that the events are real. I was actually looking forward to this movie. I am not a big fan of horror (or more specifically gore) but I did like the first one as well as Annabelle. The type of movies that creep me out are the ones that are more psychological and feel as if they could really happen. This is one of those movies. It did get a little repetitive, but the tenseness and creepy aspects really worked throughout and the movie did make me feel uneasy at times. It is becoming clear that horror movie directed by James Wan will be tense and really what horror should be. Creepy and disturbing without cutting people up or trying to hard. The relaxed pace and feel really adds to the overall tenseness and I recommend this for horror movie fans. Overall, one of the best horror movies to come out since the original Conjuring. I give this a B+.

It's hard to make an effective horror movie sequel as the initial appeal is diminished, but "The Conjuring 2" manages to overcome the problems associated with making a sequel. What's more, it's difficult to make a horror movie whose "true story" has been pretty much thoroughly discredited. How the movie goes about it is by wrapping the narrative with problems the Warrens supposedly had. It seems as if the story is told not from a "this happened, then this happened" angle but more from a theatrical one, and that's where it's most strong. The performances are great, and the direction by James Wan (whose products I personally don't like except for "The Conjuring" brand) is inspired and richly visual. He knows how to get the most effective shot possible without showing his hand too early which is a great step up from his previous efforts where there would be a great mood set and then have it ruined by something ridiculous happening. If you're curious as to what I mean, I'm referring to the "lipstick demon" in "Insidious."

I mentioned that the "true story" has been discredited. Despite if you agree or not, the movie actually includes a small part of that as a vital plot point. The main portion is that Lorraine's vision from the first is haunting her as is a demon dressed mockingly as a nun. She decides that for their safety, they shouldn't take any more cases for the time being. Naturally, there is a bizarre case in Enfield, England which calls for their expertise, and they decide they can't turn it down. Lorraine says that they will go in and investigate, but as soon as danger strikes they will be out of there. She doesn't exactly stay true to this during the movie as it shows that her empathy helped blind her from danger, but would the movie be as scary if it were safe?

I gave it four stars instead of five although I actually liked this sequel better than the original. While the original had some great scares and fantastic mood, I found the ending to be rather ridiculous and the movie slightly inconsistent. The ending here is quite powerful, and the movie feels like it's going in a singular direction rather than trying to include everything James Wan apparently admires about the Warrens. There is a very sweet scene where Ed does an Elvis impersonation for the family while playing guitar which is necessary to the soul of the movie. It doesn't want to merely terrify you but make you really care about these characters. It also proves that Patrick Wilson could effectively headline a biopic about Elvis.

Like comedies, horror movies are best if you don't give away the juice of the movie, meaning that writing a review that tells you all the funny parts of a comedy isn't helpful as is writing a review giving away all the scary parts of a horror film. Even if you haven't watched the first, I imagine that this movie will still be effective to watch even for the uninitiated. It may be a little too long by 20 or so minutes in hindsight, but I can't think of much to cut. James Wan has made the movie he wanted to make with subject material he adores with the best skill I feel he has presented so far in his career. Horror fans won't be disappointed, and those wanting a good story in the structure of a horror film will find that here.

Director James Wan delivers a superior sequel by also delivering the goods in this old fashioned style ghost story. I appreciate the fact that the tired, overdone CGI effects are used very little here. Instead, we have a superior ghost story told with goose bump inducing skill. Acting, atmosphere, direction and creep factor are all strong here. This is one of the better horror films around and a Director to watch.

 Vera Farmiga and Patrick Wilson return as Lorraine and Ed Warren, who travel to north London to help a single mother raising four children alone in a house plagued by malicious spirits. Love the fact that the film begins in Amityville and that premise alone would make an interesting movie on it's own. If I have to say anything critical, it's that the film could be a tad shorter.

The first Conjuring movie almost felt old-fashionedly refreshing with its standard creaks and jump scares.  The sequel wants to seem so scary that its prelude is the Amityville house haunting, which is meant to forebode just how terrifying the Enfield case is supposed to be.

Patrick Wilson and Vera Farmiga reprise their roles as Ed and Lorraine Warren, the nice couple (based on the real life couple) who go to demonic houses the way some couples go to Kiwanis Club meetings.  After the horrifying Amityville case, theyve sworn off getting involved in possessed homes (Lorraine has recurring visions of a demon nun killing Ed, which maybe wouldnt be a problem if Ed didn't paint the damn figure to start with).  But they are drawn into the famous case of the Enfield home outside of London, where youngest daughter Janet is showing some dispiriting signs of possession.  Along with all the furniture.

At the request of the Catholic Church (who apparently don't want to get involved with demonic possessions until they're proven real, for fear of bad public relations), The Warrens shack up in the flat with the family, barely held together by a single mom (Frances OConnor), and the plagued Janet (a wonderful performance from New Orleans native Madison Wolfe).  Some nice neighbors have taken in her sister and two brothers, and paranormal investigator Maurice Gross is there to witness, as well as the prerequisite debunker, Anita Gregory (played by Franka Potente).

Director James Wan, who helmed the original film and a Fast and Furious movie or two, knows how to ratchet up the suspense and cast an ominous gloom over a scene, but the payoff of too many scenes is predictable and punctuated with a soundtrack shriek or camera trickery.  Fans of the horror genre (possessed houses) will not find much new to raise their spirits.  Still, theres enough atmosphere and good performances that its enjoyable on its own terms.

CLICHES: A makeshift Ouija board; creepy childrens toys.  Another perfectly innocuous child's tune This Old Man is given the creepy treatment.
SURPRISES: Apparently Marilyn Manson makes a return as the demon nun! (It wasn't really Manson, but it was fun to think that).  Elvis songs soothe evil spirits.  Am I the only one finding it increasingly hard to tell the difference between Vera Farmiga and Gillian Anderson?
